\subsection{Interpretation}
\label{sec:mc_interpretation}

The hit fractions and tail frequencies reported in Sections~\ref{sec:null_tight}--\ref{sec:supplementary} are conditional frequencies under specific Monte Carlo constructions over explicitly chosen null models. They are not $p$-values~\cite{CowanCranmerGrossVitells2011,Lyons2008}, do not constitute hypothesis tests against any physical null, and should not be interpreted as evidence against chance in any objective sense. They characterize the observation's numerical behavior within the constructions we built; we draw no further inferential conclusion from them. In particular, the $0.26\%$ figure reported for the temporal trajectory and the $0.34\%$ primary random-spectrum hit fraction are not combinable into a single compound ``significance''; they probe different axes of the same observation under separate and partly overlapping constructions, and their independence is not established.

\section{Caveats and non-claims}
\label{sec:notclaims}

We have not derived $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework, and we propose no mechanism. The Monte Carlo characterization of Section~\ref{sec:robustness} reports the matchs behavior under a Koide-conditioned toy null. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders.

\paragraph{Not the only algebraic route to a comparable number.}
Rivero~\cite{Rivero2011} showed independently in 2011 that the quark triple $(s, c, b)$ with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ satisfies a Koide-like relation $Q \approx 2/3$, and that chained Koide conditions (the ``Koide waterfall'') connect lepton and quark sectors algebraically; this construction recovers $m_s$ in the same numerical neighborhood as the Soddy curvature reported here. The two routes are conceptually distinct: Rivero's construction is purely algebraic and chains Koide conditions across triples, whereas the present construction is geometric and operates on a single Koide-saturating triple via the Descartes circle theorem. Independent algebraic and geometric routes landing in the same numerical neighborhood could indicate shared underlying structure; it could equally indicate that lepton-mass combinations near $1$~GeV are not scarce near the strange-quark mass, a consideration that bears on the evidentiary weight assigned to either route individually.

\paragraph{Not a charm or bottom relation.}
$\mathcal{F}$ has units of $\text{MeV}^{1/2}$, so only $\mathcal{F}^2$ carries mass dimension one; comparisons $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \neq 2$ are not unit-invariant. Restricting to the dimensionally consistent comparison, $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx 95$~MeV is well outside both the charm range ($m_c \sim 1.3$~GeV) and the bottom range ($m_b \sim 4.2$~GeV) at any reasonable scale. We restrict the present note to the strange sector.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}

If future work were to establish that the observation is not coincidental, possible interpretations fall into three broad classes. First, the Koide relation may have a geometric origin that has not been recognized, and the Soddy connection may be its geometric content; in that case the present observation extends the same geometric structure into the strange sector via the natural mass scale of the lepton triple. Second, the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ may be the natural matching scale of some flavor mechanism that produces $m_s$ from leptonic input, in which case the observation is a datum that any such mechanism should seek to reproduce. Third, the observation may be a coincidence of the kind that Koide's relation itself might be: an unexplained numerical regularity that nonetheless remains stable as measurements improve. We do not argue for any of the three.

\paragraph{Author's tentative interpretation.}
The Koide relation has held to one part in $10^5$ for over four decades without an accepted derivation, and $\mathcal{F}^2$ is consistent with $m_s^{\msbar}$ at the natural lepton-sum scale within current lattice precision. In the author's view, regularities of this kind are best understood as shadows of underlying algebraic structure: the Descartes--Soddy construction is a visualization of an algebraic identity, not an explanation for it. The three possibilities enumerated above are offered as a neutral map of interpretations; the author does not argue for any particular one. We report the observation in the possibility that, if such an underlying algebraic structure exists and is eventually identified, the present numerical match may serve as an additional constraint to narrow the search for it.

\paragraph{Outlook.}
The present work reports a single numerical observation and deliberately stops there. Two items lie outside the scope of this paper but may be of interest as cross-references. First, the factorization $\mathcal{F}^2 = \alpha_K^2 \mu_\star$ with $\alpha_K^2 = 5/2 - \sqrt{6}$ makes the content of the numerical match explicit: what the present observation picks out is the quantity $\alpha_K^2 \mu_\star$ at the lepton-sum scale, with $\alpha_K$ a dimensionless Koide-determined coupling fixed by $Q = 2/3$. Second, a separate pre-registered analysis of the heavy-quark triple $(c, b, t)$ using the same Monte Carlo framework is reported elsewhere~\cite{Brilliant2026cbt}, with its own look-elsewhere burden and conclusions independent of the strange-sector match reported here. Neither contributes to the evidentiary base of the present observation.

\paragraph{Conclusions.}
We have introduced an ordinary-Descartes reading of the Koide lepton triple, computed the resulting outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$, and reported the numerical relation $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV, consistent with $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ (residual $+0.042$~MeV against $\pm 0.69$~MeV). The observation is stable across four prior shapes pre-registered for the Monte Carlo analysis, eight scale prescriptions, and the non-excluding lower-cutoff choices tested, and it is consistent with the $1\sigma$ band at every FLAG compilation between $2013$ and $2024$. The lepton-side quantity is essentially stationary at present precision. Both FLAG (compilations every 2--3 years; most recent FLAG~2024) and PDG (biennial Review of Particle Physics; most recent PDG~2024) are ongoing, and each successor edition will test the numerical match reported here without further analysis on the lepton side. Figure~\ref{fig:convergence} shows the narrowing of lattice uncertainties over the past decade; continued narrowing in the next cycle will sharpen or refute the agreement directly. The bare Koide relation compresses under four-curvature completion to the one-constant form $\mathcal{F}^2 = \alpha_K^2\,\mu_\star$ with $\alpha_K^2 = 5/2 - \sqrt{6}$, and that compression carries a second sub-sigma numerical match as its first non-trivial output. The result is presented as a precise numerical regularity whose theoretical status, if any, remains open.

\section*{Computational Note}

Central values, lattice-input propagation, and the null-model Monte Carlos reported in this paper are reproducible from the version-pinned GitHub repository~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}. Full protocols, the pre-registration document, and all Monte Carlo output (per-draw data, hit fractions with confidence intervals, the full $24$-function comparison family, and the temporal trajectory) are in the companion methods note~\cite{Brilliant2026methods}. Four-loop $\msbar$ running is performed via CRunDec~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.273$~GeV and $m_b(m_b) = 4.183$~GeV. Lepton inputs are PDG~2024 charged-lepton pole masses. Quark inputs are the FLAG~2024 $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ Table~11 estimate for $m_s$ and PDG~2024 summary-table values for $m_c$ and $m_b$. Total runtime for the full robustness analysis is under five minutes on a laptop.

